    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                <p> To my great comfort <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        Lows</persName> draft is just arrived, which I shall pay on Saturday. I
                    leave town on Monday. I do assure you the fault about the delivery of y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Books rests on <persName ref="pe0309">your master
                        of the ship</persName>.</p>
                <p>Be so good as to return the Letter I sent undirected.</p>
                <closer><salute>I am in much <lb/>haste y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi></salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant.</persName></signed>
                    <dateline>April 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1774.</dateline></closer>

                <postscript>
                    <p> I think you had best order some ship master to call at <persName ref="pe0026">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Whites</persName> for the
                        box of my Tours<note type="editorial">Pennant's <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0004">A tour in Scotland 1769</title></bibl> (3rd
                            edn., 1774) and <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0008">A tour in
                                    Scotland, and voyage to the Hebrides 1772</title></bibl>
                            (1774).</note> that you are so kind as to disperse. </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
